This patch fixes an early scheduler-frequency-invariance warning seen on
Sky1 ACPI systems when `cppc_cpufreq` enables fast switching before
`capacity_freq_ref` has a non-zero value.

The warning is:

    WARNING: CPU: ... at drivers/base/arch_topology.c:140 topology_set_freq_scale()

The failing path is:

 - `cpufreq_driver_fast_switch()` successfully changes frequency
 - it calls `arch_set_freq_scale(policy->related_cpus, freq,
   arch_scale_freq_ref(policy->cpu))`
 - `arch_scale_freq_ref()` returns `0`
 - `topology_set_freq_scale()` correctly warns because a zero reference
   frequency would make frequency scaling meaningless

The vendor tree already adds `topology_update_freq_ref()` for later max-frequency
changes, but that does not populate the initial reference before the first fast
switch.  A narrow fallback inside `cpufreq_driver_fast_switch()` would avoid this
one warning, but it would leave the architecture topology state unset for other
users of `capacity_freq_ref`.

Use the existing arch-topology cpufreq policy notifier instead.  Upstream skips
that notifier on ACPI systems because CPPC normally initializes capacity and
frequency references from firmware.  Some firmware, including the observed Sky1
ACPI tables, provides enough CPPC data for valid cpufreq policies but not enough
for a non-zero topology frequency reference.  In that case, keep the notifier
registered and let `init_cpu_capacity_callback()` fill only the missing ACPI
references from `policy->cpuinfo.max_freq`.

This preserves the normal ACPI/CPPC path when firmware has already provided a
reference, preserves the existing non-ACPI behavior, and fixes the warning at
the source of the bad topology state rather than special-casing one cpufreq
caller.

diff --git a/drivers/base/arch_topology.c b/drivers/base/arch_topology.c
--- a/drivers/base/arch_topology.c
+++ b/drivers/base/arch_topology.c
@@ -404,6 +404,8 @@ init_cpu_capacity_callback(struct notifier_block *nb,
 	cpumask_andnot(cpus_to_visit, cpus_to_visit, policy->related_cpus);
 
 	for_each_cpu(cpu, policy->related_cpus) {
+		if (!acpi_disabled && per_cpu(capacity_freq_ref, cpu))
+			continue;
 		per_cpu(capacity_freq_ref, cpu) = policy->cpuinfo.max_freq;
 		freq_inv_set_max_ratio(cpu,
 				       per_cpu(capacity_freq_ref, cpu) * HZ_PER_KHZ);
@@ -426,15 +428,35 @@ static struct notifier_block init_cpu_capacity_notifier = {
 	.notifier_call = init_cpu_capacity_callback,
 };
 
+static bool topology_has_missing_cpufreq_ref(void)
+{
+	int cpu;
+
+	for_each_possible_cpu(cpu) {
+		if (!per_cpu(capacity_freq_ref, cpu))
+			return true;
+	}
+
+	return false;
+}
+
 static int __init register_cpufreq_notifier(void)
 {
 	int ret;
 
 	/*
-	 * On ACPI-based systems skip registering cpufreq notifier as cpufreq
-	 * information is not needed for cpu capacity initialization.
+	 * On ACPI-based systems, CPPC normally initializes CPU capacity and the
+	 * reference frequency before cpufreq policy creation.  If every possible
+	 * CPU already has a reference frequency, cpufreq information is not
+	 * needed for CPU capacity initialization.
+	 *
+	 * Some ACPI firmware provides enough CPPC data for cpufreq policies but
+	 * leaves capacity_freq_ref unset.  Keep the notifier active for that
+	 * case so init_cpu_capacity_callback() can seed the missing references
+	 * from policy->cpuinfo.max_freq before fast-switch users call
+	 * topology_set_freq_scale().
 	 */
-	if (!acpi_disabled)
+	if (!acpi_disabled && !topology_has_missing_cpufreq_ref())
 		return -EINVAL;
 
 	if (!alloc_cpumask_var(&cpus_to_visit, GFP_KERNEL))
